	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>French tuna-seiners are accused of under-reporting tuna catches in Mozambique</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 May 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to an editorial in <i>Fish Information &amp; Services</i>, ‘Failure to comply with catch declarations under the Mozambican fisheries law has resulted in the notification of French tuna purse-seiners operating under the FPA between the EU and the Republic of Mozambique’.</p><p>In 2010, 11 French-flagged purse-seine fishing vessels were operating in the Mozambican EEZ. ‘Under the Mozambican fisheries legislation, tuna-fishing vessels are obliged to provide detailed data on catches to the competent authority upon entry and exit to the EEZ. Failure to declare, or to otherwise under-report catches, is considered a serious infraction. The protocol of the FPA between the EU and Mozambique governs the specific conditions relating to these catch declarations.’</p><p>The investigation carried out by the Mozambique General Directorate for Fisheries Administration compared tuna catches declared in the 2010 annual company report and tuna catches declared in the entry/exit reports for the 2010 fishing season. The analysis showed that four French tuna purse-seiners misreported their catches; that six vessels have, at least, one entry/exit report missing and three fishing vessels have reported total catches instead of catch per species. ‘Only 2 of the 11 French tuna purse-seiners fishing in the Mozambican EEZ have correctly reported’ their tuna catches.</p><p>The investigation resulted in the detection of two serious infractions committed by two purse-seiners, which ‘have been charged for under-reporting tuna catches in entry/exit reports, respectively 71 and 58 tonnes of tuna ... The two vessels have been notified for under-reporting catches. Once the fine and the necessary sanctions are pronounced by the minister of fisheries, the company is given eight days to pay the fine.’ Under Mozambican law catches from offending vessels could be seized and fishing licenses could be suspended or cancelled.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Press article, ‘Numerous French vessels denounced for under-reporting tuna catches’, <i>Fish Information &amp; Services</i>, 15 March 2011<br />http://www.fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?monthyear=3-2011&amp;day=15&amp;id=41174&amp;l=e&amp;country=0&amp;special=&amp;ndb=1&amp;df=0</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Under-reporting by EU fleets has been a serious issue in tuna FPAs, recognised by both parties, including in FPAs joint committees. To address this issue, some changes have been introduced in recent years, making better use of new technologies (electronic log books, better systems for sharing vessel localisation data, etc). Support has also been provided to ACP administrations, either through FPAs or through regional programmes, to improve their capacity to monitor the activities of fishing vessels. This case from Mozambique highlights how its capacity to address the problem has improved, not only with respect to detecting infractions, but also in terms of applying deterrent sanctions.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
